      <h1>About 2,000 years ago</h1>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>Greenhouse gases were emitted from Greenland at least 2,000 years ago</li>
            <li>The ancient Romans kept domesticated livestock like cows, sheep and goats which exrete methane gas</li> 
            <li>The Chinese, during the Han Dynasty, polluted by fashioning weapons, which required to burn wood <br>and rice farming brought over many methane producing bacteria</br></li> 
            <li>Agriculture increased methane emissions around the world</li>   
          </ul>
        </p>
      
      <h2>The Industrial Revolution</h2>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>The Industrial Revolution introduced many sources of water and air pollution <br>such as the increased use of coal</br></li> 
              <h2>Fun Facts</h2>
            <li>The Industrial Revolution pollution caused "anti-pollution" days such as: Earth Day, Clean Air Act(1970), and Clean Water Act(1972)</li>
            <li>In the 13th century King Eward I of England, in an effort to reduce pollution, threatened Londoners with penalties if they kept using sea-coal</li>
          </ul>
        </p> 
      
      <h3><strong>From the 20's to Modern Day</strong></h3>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>In 2007 46% of all americans resided in counties with unhealthy levels of ozone, or smog</li> 
            <li>In 1969, chemical released into the Cuyahoga River in Ohio, which caused it to burst into flames<br>this made the waterway a symbol of how industrial pollution was destroying american nature</br></li>
            <li>In 2007, CNN reported that "up to 500 million tons of heavy metals, solvents and toxic sludge slip into the global water supply every year" </li>
            <li>According to UNESCO, 70% of industrial waste is dumped untreated into rivers and lakes </li>
            <li>According to GreenPeace, around 70% of China's lakes and rivers are polluted from industrial waste, this causes 300 million people to use these polluted water supplies</li>
            <li>In 2006, the ENS reported that more than 62% industrial and municipal facilities across the country<br>discharged more pollution into U.S. waterways than their Clean Water Act permits</br></li>
            <li>In 1989, the Exxon Valdez crashed and spilled about 11 million gallons of crude oil into the sea<br>This oil spill caused a 3,000 square-mile oil slick, killed thousands of birds,fish and other animal-life in the area</br></li>
         </ul>
        </p>  
